  <static seed="62" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{1}{9} + \frac{47}{54}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{53}{54}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>9</m> and <m>54</m> is <m>54</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{1}{9}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>54</m>, we multiply <m>6</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned} \frac{1}{9} \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 6}{9 \cdot 6}\\ \amp  = \frac{6}{54} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>The second fraction already has the common denominator.</p>
<p>Finally, we can do the addition. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{1}{9} + \frac{47}{54}
        \amp = \frac{6}{54} + \frac{47}{54} \\
        \amp = \frac{6 + 47}{54} \\
        \amp = \frac{53}{54}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{53}{54}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
